'''Edwin Grant Dexter''' (born 1868, date of death unknown) was an [[United States|American]] educator, born at [[Calais, Maine|Calais]], [[Maine|Me.]] He graduated in 1891 from [[Brown University]], where he taught for a year and then (between 1892 and 1899) was science master of Colorado Springs High School, director of the Colorado Springs Summer School of Science, Philosophy, and Languages, and [[professor]] of psychology in the Normal School at [[Greeley, Colorado|Greeley, Colo.]]  In 1899 he gained a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] at [[Columbia University]] and the higher diploma of [[Teachers College, Columbia University|Teachers College]].  From then until 1907 he served at the [[University of Illinois system|University of Illinois]] in various capacities &mdash; as professor of pedagogy and psychology, director of the summer term, director of the School of Education, and [[dean (education)|dean]].  He became commissioner of education in [[Puerto Rico|Porto Rico]] and chancellor of the [[University of Puerto Rico|University of Porto Rico]] in 1907.  He was president of the [[National Society for the Scientific Study of Education]] in 1905-06 and president of the child-study section of the [[National Education Association]] in 1905-07.  Besides serving as associate editor of the ''Internationales Archivar für Schulhygiene'' and of the ''Jahrschrift für Körpeliche Erziehung'' and contributing some 50 articles to scientific and educational journals, he was author of:  
* {{cite book |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000426042 |via=HathiTrust |title=A History of Education in the United States |year=1904 |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York}}
* ''Weather Influences'' (1904)

