'''George John Griffiths''' [[Queen's Service Order|QSO]] (1933–29 January 2014) was a New Zealand historian, writer, and journalist.

Griffiths started his newspaper career in 1954 at the ''[[Southland Times]]'', based in [[Invercargill]], moving to [[Dunedin]] and joining the ''[[Otago Daily Times]]'' in 1962. He was to work at the latter paper until his retirement in 1991.<ref name="ODT">"[https://www.odt.co.nz/news/dunedin/historian-dies-80 Historian dies at 80]," ''[[Otago Daily Times]]'', 30 January 2014. Retrieved 22 April 2018.</ref>

In 1978, Griffiths co-founded [[Otago Heritage Books]], which published books on the history of the southern [[South Island]], many of which were edited by Griffiths, and also operated as a central Dunedin bookshop which became a hub for local writers and historians.<ref>McLean, Gavin "[http://beattiesbookblog.blogspot.co.nz/2014/02/george-griffiths-rip.html George Griffiths R.I.P.],' ''Beattie's Book Blog – unofficial homepage of the New Zealand book community'', 3 February 2014. Retrieved 22 April 2018.</ref> He also wrote numerous books, many of which were published by Otago Heritage Books, most of them relating to [[History of Otago|Otago history]],<ref name="ODT"/> and contributed many biographical articles to the [[Dictionary of New Zealand Biography]].

Griffiths was named as a [[University of Otago]] [[Hocken Fellowship|Hocken fellow]] in 1998.<ref name="commun">"[http://thecommunityarchive.org.nz/node/78779/description Griffiths, George John, Dr : Business, research and personal papers]," ''thecommunityarchive.org.nz''. Retrieved 22 April 2018.</ref> He was also named Dunedin's Citizen of the Year in 1999, and in the same year was awarded a [[Queen's Service Order]] for services to the community, and was also awarded an honorary doctorate by the [[University of Otago]].<ref name="ODT"/>

Griffiths died in early 2014. Many of his personal papers are now held as part of the [[Hocken Library]] collection.<ref name="commun"/>

