{{context|date=November 2011}} *Around 2000 BC, the proto-Illyrian culture begins to form when indigenous Danubian farmers were invaded by warrior-herders belonging to the [[Yamnaya]] culture from the Plateau of [[Phrygia]]. They inhabit the western half of the Balkan Peninsula.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-s0UAQAAIAAJ&q=%E2%80%9Cillyrians%E2%80%9D+%E2%80%9C2000+BC%E2%80%9D&dq=%E2%80%9Cillyrians%E2%80%9D+%E2%80%9C2000+BC%E2%80%9D&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiD2ae-xZzeAhWHAcAKHeBbBoAQ6AEISTAH|title=Albania|last=Young|first=Antonia|last2=Hodgson|first2=John|last3=Young|first3=Nigel|date=1997-01-01|publisher=Clio Press|isbn=9781851092604|language=en}}</ref> *1200BC (or perhaps earlier), some Illyrians begin a movement to Gaul, Spain, England, northern and central Italy, Poland and even Scandinavia. <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NLcWAQAAIAAJ&q=%E2%80%9Cproto-illyrians%E2%80%9D&dq=%E2%80%9Cproto-illyrians%E2%80%9D&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiDi7PJrp_eAhXKCcAKHfOwCKYQ6AEIMjAC|title=The Illyrians: history and culture|last=Stipčević|first=Aleksandar|date=1977|publisher=Noyes Press|isbn=9780815550525|language=en}}</ref> *1000 BC, Illyrians mining salt in Gmunden, present-day Austria; by 900 BC they had lost their silver mines in Oberzeiring to the Celts. *8th century BC, Illyrian culture begins to flourish on the coasts of the Adriatic, centered in [[Glasinac culture|Glasinac]] and [[Shkodra]]. *5th century: Illyrians mentioned by Herodotus, inhabiting [[Dalmatia]], [[Bosnia]] and [[Herzegovina]], with a major center at [[Shkodra]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTbc1GIAwcIC&pg=PA84&dq=Swastika+illyrian&hl=en&ei=sridTpG1HIX64QTsop3RCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Illyrian&f=false Harry Mountain: The Celtic Encyclopedia, Volume 1, p. 83]</ref> *360 B.C., the Illyrians attack the Macedonians, after obtaining tribute from them. [[Perdiccas]], the king of the Macedonians is killed in battle together with 400 of his soldiers.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?ei=iiejTt6wF4TJsga7sOCRAw&ct=result&id=NLcWAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Illyrians%22+%22year%22&q=%22In+the+year+360+BC+the+Illyrians+again+attacked+the+Macedonians%2C+after+previously+having+succeeded+in+obtaining+tribute+from+them.+The+Macedonian+king+Perdiccas+was+totally+defeated+and+perished+on+the+battlefield+%22#search_anchor Aleksandar Stipčević: The Illyrians : history and culture, page 43]</ref> *Before 336 B.C., Perdiccas' brother, Philip drives the Illyrians from his territory.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-yd1huHoXJwC&pg=PA48&dq=%22the+illyrians%22+%22in+the+year%22&hl=en&ei=wCmrTs3lOY-WswaroI3-Dw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22the%20illyrians%22%20%22in%20the%20year%22&f=false |title=The Celts: A History - Dáithí Ó hÓgáin - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref> *218 B.C., [[Scerdilaidas]], an ally of Macedonia helps Philip during the Social War.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Oe1u1H_OSMC&pg=PA95&dq=%22the+illyrian%22+%22in+the+year%22&hl=en&ei=PSyrToC3LIaWswb3lKzjDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CFYQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=scerdilaidas&f=false |title=Rome and the Mediterranean to 133 B.C. - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref>
